temperament as the authors are different in their interests and methods. Taken together, the essays of American Labyrinth illustrate how intellectual historians, operating in many different registers at once and ranging from the theoretical to the political, can provide telling insights for understanding a public sphere fraught with conflict.In order to understand why people are ready to fight over cultural symbols and political positions we must have insight into how ideas organize, enliven, and define our lives. Ultimately, as Haberski and Hartman show in this volume, the best route through our contemporary American labyrinth is the path that traces our practical and lived ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory. 4aSociology & Social Science. 4aU.S. History.  aIntellectual History.  aIntellectual life.  aLegal Fundamentalism.  aUS intellectual history.  aamerican Intellectual History.  aamerican Intellectual life.  aamerican historiorography.  aamerican history.  aamerican social history.  aamerican studies.  abipartisan Intellectual History.  acontemporary intellectual life in America.  acontemporary issues.  ahistorians.  ahistorical experience.  ahistoriography.  ahistory of political thought.  aintellectual historian essays.  aintellectual historians.  aintellectual history studies.  aparty politics Intellectual History.  apolitical activism.  apolitical analysis.  apolitical commentary.  apolitical culture.  apolitical debate.  apolitical discourse.  apolitical division.  apolitical history.  apolitical ideologies.  apolitical ideology.  apolitical institutions.  apolitical leadership.  apolitical literature.  apolitical movements.  apolitical philosophy.  apolitical science anthology.  apolitical science essay.  apolitical s